{
  "texts": [
    "SOPool (Wang and Ji 2020) further proposes the use of second-order information of nodes to enhance the pooling operation.",
    "Compared with the existing graph pooling methods, second-order pooling can make full use of all the node information on the graph and its second-order information, thus making its pooling function more powerful.",
    "In addition, considering the importance of distributional knowledge for improving the performance of graph-level tasks, DKEPool (Chen et al. 2022) introduces distributional knowledge so that the graph pooling process can capture not only the spatial relationships among nodes but also the distributional properties of the node features.",
    "Methods such as DEMO-Net (Wu et al. 2019) and GMT (Baek et al. 2102) further explore the Hilbert kernel space based on specific metrics and graph multiset pooling for graph representation learning methods, respectively.",
    "In particular, GMT (Baek et al. 2102) can capture structural dependencies and task relevance among nodes by combining an improved multi-attention mechanism with a self-attention mechanism to generate more discriminative graph embeddings."
  ]
}